Repository stuff 

    Google code is hosting this shebang.  http://code.google.com/p/mad-man/
    
    Goto https://code.google.com/hosting/settings 
        There are two options for authentication 
        1. Password prompted fashion
            git clone https://chris.t.sherman@code.google.com/p/mad-man/ 
            -enter password and its cloned 

        2. Automated  
            setup ~/.netrc 
            "machine code.google.com login <your gs mail>@gmail.com [generated googlecode.com password]"
            chmod 600 ~/.netrc 
            git clone https://code.google.com/p/mad-man/

    Committing and the fun stuff...
        1. git add * (if you added any files) 
        2. git commit -m "put a message in your commit dangit"
        3. git remote add origin https://code.google.com/p/mad-man/ (probably not needed anyways)
        4. git push origin master (push back to master, google repo) 


----------------------------------------------------------------------
Requirements 
    [for specific installation instructions see each packages documentation]
    -iPython (http://ipython.org/) 
        enhanced interpreter with goodies 
    -clint (http://pypi.python.org/pypi/clint/0.2.1)
        command line interface tools (text formatting, progress bars, goodies for cli environment) 
    -fabric (http://docs.fabfile.org/en/1.4.0/index.html) 
        for cross madman deploymeny synching - its a nice package 
    -django 1.3.1 + (pip, yum, manually) 
        for django version < 1.3 just "pip install django --upgrade" 
        if that doesn't work to upgrade, find location of django and remove it 
    -django-staticfiles (pip)       --> Package for static files 
    -django-debug-toolbar (pip)     --> Debug toolbar for Django 
    -django-profiles (pip)          --> Django user profile app 
    -django-registration (pip)      --> registration app
    -django_extensions (pip)        --> some bad ass django commands 
    -django-tagging (pip)           --> django app for tagging objects 
    -mptt (pip)                     --> this is the tree library 

    -jit (javascript library, comes built into repo but worth mentioning we will use this for library/tree visuals)

